Greek language has a flexible word order, which means that the arrangement of words can vary without changing the meaning of a sentence. 

Common errors in Greek often involve incorrect placement of adjectives and the use of articles,  particularly in relation to gender and number agreement.

Greek Language Word Order

Greek has a flexible word order, allowing for variations in the arrangement of words without altering the meaning of a sentence. 

This flexibility is due to the inflection of endings, which indicates the grammatical function of nouns and verbs.

Common Word Orders

    Subject-Verb-Object (SVO): 
    
    This is a familiar structure, similar to English.
    
    Variations: 
    
    Other arrangements, such as Verb-Subject-Object (VSO) or Object-Subject-Verb (OSV), are also grammatically correct.

Typical Errors in Greek

Common Mistakes

    Adjective Placement: 
    
    Adjectives must agree in gender and number with the nouns they modify. 
    
    Incorrect placement can lead to confusion.
    
    Article Usage: 
    
    The definite article must match the gender and number of the noun. 
    
    Errors often occur when omitting or misplacing articles.

Error Corrections

